Kingdom","England":"Anglie","Southampton, Hampshire, England":"Southampton, Hampshire, Anglie"},"da":{"1278–1302":"1278–1302","1270–1329":"1270–1329","1300–1327":"1300–1327","1327":"1327","1302":"1302","1278":"1278","1300":"1300","about 1300":"omkring 1300","1270":"1270","1329":"1329","1290":"1290","Shirburn, Oxfordshire, England":"Shirburn, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Southampton, Hampshire, England":"Southampton, Hampshire, England"},"nl":{"1278–1302":"1278–1302","1270–1329":"1270–1329","1300–1327":"1300–1327","1327":"1327","1302":"1302","1278":"1278","1300":"1300","about 1300":"circa 1300","1270":"1270","1329":"1329","1290":"1290","Shirburn, Oxfordshire, England":"Shirburn, Oxfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England","Southampton, Hampshire, England":"Southampton, Hampshire, England"},"en":{"1278–1302":"1278–1302","1270–1329":"1270–1329","1300–1327":"1300–1327","1327":"1327","1302":"1302","1278":"1278","1300":"1300","about 1300":"about 1300","1270":"1270","1329":"1329","1290":"1290","Shirburn, Oxfordshire, England":"Shirburn, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Southampton, Hampshire, England":"Southampton, Hampshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"St.","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized spelling of French   St  .   Denis  ."],"variants":[{"name":"St","meanings":["Americanized spelling of French   St  .   Denis  ."]},{"name":"Denis","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Camille, Jacques, Armand, Marcel, Andre, Pierre, Serge, Yvan, Alphonse, Edouard, Francois, Gaetane.  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Jorge, Roberto, Angel, Francisco, Joaquin, Juan, Manuel, Miguel, Ramon, Rolando.","French, Walloon, Breton, West Indian (mainly Haiti), German, Dutch, English, and Portuguese; Spanish and Galician (<b>Denís</b>): from the personal name <i>Denis</i>, Spanish and Galician <i>Denís</i>, from Latin <i>Dionysius</i> ‘(follower) of Dionysos’ (see   Dennis  ). Compare   Dennee  .","Ukrainian and Rusyn: variant transliteration of   Denys  , a cognate of 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Philabert","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Fernand, Mirielle, Pascale, Pierrot.","French: from the personal name <i>Philibert</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Filuberht</i>, composed of the elements <i>fila</i> ‘much, very’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright’, which was borne by a 7th-century Christian saint, abbot of Jumièges. The spelling has been influenced by personal names of Greek origin based on <i>philein</i> ‘to love’, e.g.   Philip  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Philbert","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Monique.  German Kurt.","French and German (Bavaria): from the personal name <i>Philbert</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Filuberht</i> (see   Philibert  )."]},{"name":"Philip","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Varughese, Mathai, Babu, Reji, Anil, Binu, Neena, Prema, Raju, Reena, Susheela, Aleykutty.","Scottish, English, German, Dutch, and Jewish: from the Greek personal name <i>Philippos</i> (from <i>philein</i> ‘to love’ + <i>hippos</i> ‘horse’). In the New Testament this name is borne by one of the apostles; it was also borne by various other early Christian saints. It owes part of its popularity to the medieval romances about Alexander the Great, whose father was Philip of Macedon. As a Jewish name, it represents a borrowing of the personal name from Christians. As a Highland Scottish surname, it represents an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Fhilib</b> ‘son of Philip’. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, e.g. Spanish   Felipe  , Catalan <b>Felip</b>, Polish, Czech, Slovak, Slovenian or Croatian   Filip  , Albanian   Filipi  , and their derivatives (see examples at   Philips  ). The name <i>Philip</i> is also found among Christians in southern India (compare   Philipose   and   Pothen  ), but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US. Compare   Phillip  .","French (southern) and Breton (Finistère): variant of   Philippe  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":12,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Alice St. Philabert was born in 1278, in Southampton, Hampshire, England. She had at least 1 son with John St. Claire. She lived in Shirburn, Oxfordshire, England in 1299. She died in 1302, in England, at the age of 24."},"et":{"1278–1302":"1278–1302","1270–1329":"1270–1329","1300–1327":"1300–1327","1327":"1327","1302":"1302","1278":"1278","1300":"1300","about 1300":"umbes 1300","1270":"1270","1329":"1329","1290":"1290","Shirburn, Oxfordshire, England":"Shirburn, Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Eng